##A global pandemic is just around the corner | the cover of CAIJING

I-CAIJING

CAIJING magazine official Wechat. "CAIJING" magazine, sponsored by the China Securities Market Research Center, was first published in 1998, adhering to the news concept of "independence, exclusiveness and originality" , and is known for authoritative, impartial and professional reporting, it is a must-read publication for policy-makers, researchers and managers in the field of politics and economics.

New Crown Disease in China has been initially contained, but in six continents to accelerate the spread of multiple shocks, World Health Organization Organization has not identified as a "pandemic" , a coordinated fight against the disease has a long way to go

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Wen | CAIJING correspondent in Washington, Jin Yan correspondent in Caijing, Cai Tingyi, Beijing

CAIJING is a London based journalist and contributing writer to Jiang Weide in Tehran

Editor | Hao Zhou

After more than a month of prevention and control, although China's epidemic data is still growing, but the number of newly diagnosed infections continued to decline, the number of discharged cases continued to increase, the epidemic spread was initially contained. But outside China, South Korea, Japan, Italy, Iran and other countries have many cluster infections, the rapid increase of confirmed cases, the situation of the spread of the epidemic in the world caused great concern.

As a result of lax control and the spread of the epidemic in these countries of new concern, cases related to Iran have been imported into neighbouring countries such as Lebanon, the United Arab Emirates, Bahrain, Iraq, Kuwait, Oman and Pakistan, cases associated with Italy have been imported into Algeria, Austria, Croatia, Germany, Spain and Switzerland.

As of 1700 hours Beijing Time on March 2,64 countries outside China had reported 8,774 confirmed cases, including 128 deaths, according to the World Health Organization. On February 26th, for the first time, more new cases were reported outside China than inside. On March 2nd there were nine times as many new arrivals in a single day abroad as in China itself.

Still, World Health Organization does not want to rush to declare a global "pandemic" "without a careful and clear analysis of the facts. ". Who director-general Tan Desai stressed that, "The COVID-19 has been declared a public health emergency of international concern by the WHO, which is the highest level of alert by the WHO. Using the term 'global pandemic' in a hasty manner does not yield any tangible benefits, but only serious risks, amplifying unnecessary and unfounded fears and stigmatization and paralysing social systems. "

World Health Organization is monitoring the situation 24 hours a day and is in constant communication with experts inside and outside the organization if the outbreak does reach the point where a "global pandemic" needs to be declared, he said, who will not hesitate. "At the moment, we are not seeing sustained and intensive community transmission, nor are we seeing mass severe illness and death, " he said

Passengers Rush during the morning rush hour on the Tokyo Metro in Shinagawa Station, Japan, on Feb. 8. FIGURE / method new

South Korea: New World Church brings disaster

The outbreak began to heat up on Feb. 21, and confirmed cases doubled in just a few days, making South Korea the worst affected region outside COVID-19, the Korean government's containment-based epidemic prevention policy has also been forced to seek disaster reduction.

South Korea has 1,766 confirmed cases and 13 deaths.

With the number of cases rapidly rising, South Korea's epidemic prevention authorities were too late to investigate and block the source of infection in each case.

South Korea's government held an emergency meeting on Feb. 23, when President Moon jae-in declared a state of emergency, raising the alert level for infectious diseases from "alert" to "serious" at the highest level. This is South Korea since the 2009 H1N1 influenza, once again issued the highest level of infectious disease alert, the government in accordance with statutory standards can be issued at any time to suspend schools, prohibit group activities and other emergency orders. According to the relevant departments, February 23 to March 3 will be whether South Korea can effectively control the outbreak of the time window.

South Korea's rapid rise in the outbreak is mainly due to two clusters of infection, especially in the fourth largest city of Daegu, South Korea's "New World" Church; the other source of infection is gyeongsang-do-do-gyeongdo-jun Dannan hospital. Since North Gyeongsang Province is the home town of Lee Man-Hee, the founder of the New World Church, members of the Church attended the funeral of the founder's brother at the hospital, the Center for Disease Control and Prevention, under the Ministry of Health and Welfare, concluded that the infection at Daenam hospital also came from the church.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Workers prepare to disinfect a traffic hub in Dongdaegu Station, Taegu, South Korea, on February 29,2020. Figure / Fachen

Kim Dong-hyun, an epidemiologist at Hanlin medical school in South Korea, said that South Korea has passed the stage where the government's epidemic prevention department can control the epidemic independently, and now it has entered a critical period when the whole society must cooperate in the epidemic prevention.

South Korea's "31st patient" has become the country's first "super spreader" after a reset investigation. The "31st case" was a woman born in 1959 who had fever since February 10, tested positive for the virus on February 17 and was diagnosed positive on February 18 as a result of the car accident, which began on February 7 and began to travel to local clinics for treatment. The next day, 13 new cases were reported in Taegu and North Gyeongsang Province, all of which were traced to the "31st patient, " and South Korean media reported that doctors at the clinic had advised her to be screened for the virus but had refused. She attended church services four times after the onset of symptoms and had contact with more than 1,160 people. South Korea's epidemic prevention system has since faced severe challenges.

The infected Xintiandi Church members developed symptoms mainly between February 7-10 and 14-18, and the Korean Center for Disease Control and Prevention concluded that church worship may have been the main occasion for the spread of the virus.

Members of the New World Church, which has a population of at least 210,000 and more than 1,000 strongholds in South Korea, tend to hide their participation in church activities, as well as their secret proselytism from their families. "New World" Church in the early reluctant to cooperate with the epidemic prevention, the submission of the list of believers and contact information is not complete, some media pointed out that the Church asked believers to receive the epidemic prevention phone calls to deny participation in activities misleading epidemic prevention personnel. Epidemic Prevention officials later said that if the church does not cooperate will take legal action.

Moon, in particular, said after an emergency meeting on Feb. 23 that the government would close Xintiandi's churches across the country and conduct a full investigation of believers. The South Korean government has declared Taegu and gyeongsang-do-gyeongdo-gyeongju as "special infectious disease management areas" .

The Xintiandi outbreak also included the military, where a soldier in Jeju Island had been infected by 5 p.m. on Feb. 27 after leaving for a holiday in Taegu to meet his girlfriend on Feb. 20, south Korea's armed forces have quarantined at least 9,990 people, with 25 infected, and the U.S. and South Korea have postponed joint military exercises scheduled for March 9 because of the outbreak.

Given the rapid warming of the epidemic, ordinary South Koreans'normal lives have begun to be affected. The South Korean government announced that the new school year for kindergartens, primary and secondary schools across the country will be postponed from March 2 to March 9.

In addition to announcing a one week delay, the Daegu city government also ordered 1,324 kindergartens in the city to close and 252 geriatric medical facilities to restrict access for outsiders. In addition to cancelling major events held in Daegu, many government departments have switched to working from home.

"We felt as if the centre of the city had been hit by a bomb and there was no one there... people on the road were wearing masks, and many places needed to be taken to get in, and there was no service without masks, " Meredith Khanloo, an American who lives near the New World Church in Taegu, told CAIJING.

Ms. Park, who lives in Seoul and works as a chinese-korean translator, angrily told Caijing that the new coronaviruses' epidemic in South Korea was caused by "Xintiandi" believers. "those people are not in their right mind. We were not worried about the new coronavirus, but now the situation has completely changed and we are beginning to worry and even feel uneasy. " Ms. Park's son just went through graduation on Feb. 14, at the time, South Korea had no idea of the new coronavirus epidemic.

Meredith, who has two children, expressed concern that she and many South Korean mothers will not be able to get their children to school on time for the new school day unless she believes the epidemic is under control, "mothers are very concerned that their children will be isolated or treated in hospital, " she said.

To contain the outbreak as soon as possible, the central government is preparing a new budget to assist the governments of Taegu and North Gyeongsang Province to implement an outbreak blockade, "tight network" to block further community transmission.

In addition, the South Korean government has allocated 5 billion won (28.88 million yuan) for 14 days of isolation and face masks for Chinese students, as 38,000 Chinese students will return to the country as universities begin to open.

Italy: Europe's worst disaster zone

Italy on January 30, a husband and wife tourists from Wuhan infected with the new coronavirus, the country's first confirmed case. Italy then declared a six-month state of emergency and suspended all flights to and from China. There has been no significant increase in confirmed cases in Italy for some time since then.

But the situation took a turn for the worse on 22 February, when Italy recorded 149 new cases in two days, three of which died within 48 hours. By 1800 on 27 February, the cumulative number of cases in Italy had reached 650, with 17 deaths.

Most of the confirmed cases reported in Italy came from the northern regions of Lombardy and Veneto. Two of the worst hit areas contribute 30% of the country's GDP to Italy's economic heartland.

Following an emergency cabinet meeting on February 22, Italian Prime Minister Contes announced a series of emergency measures that night, including the closure of 11 municipalities in the Lombardy and Veneto regions. Access to the blocked area is currently controlled by the police, all public activities are suspended and traffic is restricted, affecting about 50,000 people. Violators of the quarantine requirements will be punished with up to three months in prison or a fine of up to 206 euros.

Three Serie A games scheduled for Monday night have been postponed due to the rapid spread of COVID-19 pneumonia in Italy, including a home game against Sampdoria. The Italian Ministry of Education has issued a notice requiring universities in the Lombardy, Veneto and Emilia-Romagna regions to suspend teaching until February 29.

Zhou Minxue is a Chinese student at the University of Turin in the city of Turin, which is part of the Piedmont region. Although not part of the three regions, there have been six confirmed cases. She received a notice from the school at 8 pm on the 23rd to suspend classes until the 29th. The resumption of classes is still pending further notice. "I was worried about my family, but now my family is worried about me, " Zhou min-xue, from Ezhou, told Caijing. She can no longer buy hand sanitizer, hand sanitizer and face masks at nearby pharmacies.

On February 23, Zhou min-xue went to a supermarket to buy food. She saw that the goods on the shelves were adequate. But another Chinese student living in Milan found that the shelves of the supermarket where he went were almost completely sold out. "It wasn't like this the day before, " he told Caijing.

Milan is the capital of the region of Lombardy, although confirmed cases are mainly concentrated in the southern towns of Milan, but out of concern to control the spread of the virus, Milan Cathedral will be temporarily closed to visitors until February 25; The Teatro Alla Scala in Milan announced on the 23rd that it was suspending its theatrical performances; schools in Milan were closed for a week.

The spread of the virus in Italy has also affected the situation of the local Chinese. At the end of January, a Music Academy in Rome, Italy, suspended classes for students from East Asian countries. A Chinese student studying in Turin told CAIJING that a teenager covered his mouth while avoiding him on the subway two weeks ago. But beyond that, there were no more unpleasant experiences. Images of vandalism or anti-china demonstrations against Chinese supermarkets on social media have also proved to be rumours.

But a Chinese woman became a victim of racism. On Feb. 20, a Chinese man who had lived in Turin for years was attacked by two Italians. According to the Italian "News" reported on the 23rd, the time of the incident in the daytime, the location of Turin City Center. "virus, get out of Turin, " the Chinese woman tried to explain, even though she was Chinese, when two Italians in their forty approached her at a traffic light and shouted obscenities at her, doesn't mean she has the virus. But the man continued to abuse her, and one of the women he was traveling with hit her. The mayor of Turin, Appendino, condemned the move as despicable.

For Chinese in Italy, the question is whether or not to wear a mask when one can buy one? In the eyes of locals, wearing a mask is only necessary in case of illness, while Chinese see wearing a mask as a way to protect themselves or others. With only one mask in her hand, Zhou min-xue decided to go out less. After witnessing the outbreak in her hometown, she was worried about Italians'lack of vigilance against the virus.

Iran: Further isolated due to the outbreak

On Feb. 19,28 days after the blockade in Wuhan, Hubei Province, China, Florida, two new cases of pneumonia were first reported in Iran, resulting in death. In the following week, the number of confirmed cases rose in a straight line, with a cumulative total of 388 cases and 34 deaths in Iran as of February 28 local time.

Based on the number of deaths as a proportion of confirmed cases, the fatality rate of the epidemic in Iran is 8.8 per cent, which is far higher than that of the concentrated and severe Hubei Province of China, which currently has a fatality rate of about 4 per cent.

Exactly how the virus got to Iran remains a mystery. According to a survey released by the Iranian authorities, the first confirmed cases were found in Qom Qom, who had the most confirmed cases, and most of the other confirmed cases had a history of travel by Qom. Qom Is Iran's Shiite holy city, about two hours'drive from Tehran, and the city's Qom Hawza is one of the world's most prestigious religious schools, the Mausoleum of Fatimah Zahra Masouma is considered one of the holiest places in Shia Islam.

"there is more than a 90 percent chance that the virus was introduced from China to Iran, especially Qom, " Iran's health minister, Nuri Namaki, said in an interview. But who brought it in, workers, students, merchants, travelers in Qom? There's no exact answer. He also said that one of Qom's deaths was that of an Iranian businessman who had traveled to China during the outbreak, so it was also possible that the Iranian businessman had contracted the virus in China and brought it back to Iran.

In addition to the high fatality rate, the epidemic in Iran has also shown itself to be very egalitarian. On February 25, Iran's Deputy Minister of Health, Ali Kharezi, also announced that he had been diagnosed with new coronavirus pneumonia, iran's Vice President for women and Family Affairs, Masumeeb Teka, and the chairman of the National Security and Foreign Affairs Committee of the Iranian parliament, Moujtaba, were also confirmed infected on the 27th. According to Halich, the virus "does not distinguish between high and low. ". Iran's presidential spokesman, Rabi Iran, had spent much time with Harazi at the same press conference. Both President Rohani and Rabi were tested for the virus immediately after news of the diagnosis, sources said, but both tested negative on Feb. 26. In addition, the district chief of Tehran's thirteen districts and a member of the national parliament, Sadji, were also confirmed to be infected.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A worker takes the temperature of a passenger at the Al Najaf International Airport in Iran on February 21,2020. Figure / Fachen

After the outbreak, schools in 10 provinces were closed, national sports events, concerts and art exhibitions were canceled, all cinemas and public leisure venues were closed, and Tehran also banned large gatherings such as weddings in public places, the city of Shiraz has closed popular attractions such as the pink mosque, the Gullah province has banned visits by relatives of patients, and public transport in cities such as buses and subways requires regular disinfection.

After some discussion, Iran has announced the cancellation of the February 28 mass worship. At the same time, Iran will restrict access to places of worship such as the Imam Reza Shrine in Mashhad and the Fatima Masumeh Shrine in Qom, requiring worshippers to wear face masks, carry their own hand sanitizer and show health information.

In fact, making such a decision is not easy for the combination of politics and religion in Iran. Friday prayers are an extremely important part of life for Muslims. Earlier, some clerics had said that reading the Koran could ward off the virus. Some clerics said that worshipping at the Holy Shrine could cure the disease. But scientists told the Iranian government that the risk of a large-scale gathering at the time of the outbreak was extremely high, so Friday prayers were canceled, this is an extremely difficult decision for Iran.

Even so, the measures taken by Iran and China's all-out Defense of the situation is still relatively lax, not to "seal off" the intention. President Rohani said Feb. 26, "The state has not decided to isolate any city. People should not listen to the rumors about the city. All the materials for daily life are provided adequately. " The mobilization of resources needed for the closure of the city as well as the affordability of the country's economy, is Too much for Iran to bear.

Just like the Great Flood, when you can't block it up, you can only choose to block it up. The Supreme Leader's Foreign Affairs Adviser and prominent Iranian pediatrician, Dr. Velayati, appeared on television in a white lab coat and told the public that "the new coronavirus is less lethal than the flu. ". "Most infected people don't need to go to the hospital, but can rest at home and take water and vitamin supplements, " said Vice Health Minister Khaleesi, who was in good spirits in the video he made.

As the country is trying to "cool down" the epidemic, there is no panic among the public. But that is only one reason, and a large part of it is religious, which makes many people indifferent to life and death. One supermarket official explained his reason for not wearing a mask as "not getting sick, it's all in God's hands. ".

The Iranian people have not taken good protection measures while the epidemic is spreading. The number of people wearing masks on the streets is only about 10% . The traffic jam in Tehran has not been eased because of the epidemic, most people are just going about their business as usual. More interestingly, due to the closure of schools, some students even went on holiday in groups near the Caspian Sea in northern Iran, where there were also confirmed cases in the city, which led to a direct call from the Ministry of Health, "I didn't suspend you to travel. Stay in your dorms. "

Although most people appear to be in a stable mood, pharmacies have run out of face masks, alcohol and disinfectant. Iran, which has been under sanctions for a long time, is indeed unable to cope with the rise in the demand for medical care arising from the large-scale outbreak of the epidemic.

Whether Iran's virus originated in China remains to be seen, but confirmed cases in many countries have been confirmed to have been "transported" through Iran.

On 20 February, the sixth confirmed case in British Columbia, Canada, was a woman in her 30s who had returned from Iran. The first case reported in Lebanon on Tuesday was a 45 year old Lebanese woman who had returned from a trip to Qom. A 70-year-old Iranian tourist and his 64-year-old wife were among two more confirmed cases in the United Arab Emirates Tuesday. According to statistics, as of February 27, the number of confirmed cases transmitted by Iran was 43 in Kuwait, 2 in Lebanon, 4 in Iraq, 26 in Bahrain, 2 in Oman, 2 in the United Arab Emirates, 1 in Pakistan and 1 in Canada, another Chinese man was diagnosed after returning to China from Iran.

When Iran became the "drug source" in the Middle East, all countries urgently shut down air and land traffic with Iran. In addition to the countries from which the confirmed case of Iran was found, Turkey, Tajikistan and other countries also cut off ties with Iran, iran is almost an island. The Chinese who are still in Iran are horrified to find that direct flights between Iran and China have been cancelled due to the Chinese epidemic, and the return routes that had previously been diverted through cities such as Dubai, Moscow and Istanbul have also been blocked, there's no turning back.

US: Preparing for the worst

The U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) said Feb. 26 that there have been 60 confirmed cases in the United States, most of them from passengers evacuated from the Japanese ship "Diamond Princess. " There were also three cases of expatriates evacuated from Wuhan. As far as cases found in the United States are concerned, the CDC's web site shows that there are currently 14 confirmed cases, 12 of which have a history of travel to China, and 2 of which are human to human transmission between close contacts.

U. S. health officials say the outbreak has the potential to become a global "pandemic" that could spread to communities in the United States sooner or later. As the Donald Trump government faces more pressure to prevent the spread of the new coronavirus, President Donald Trump and officials from the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention attended a press conference on the afternoon of February 26 local time.

Donald Trump announced the appointment of Vice President Michel Pense as chief of staff for the fight against the new coronavirus, given Michel Pense's experience in health policy during his time at the List of Governors of Indiana. Michel Pense will be responsible for coordinating medical and other professionals to prevent the spread of the virus in the United States.

New-cap pneumonia could quickly become a "pandemic, " Jake Endy, a professor of medicine at the University of Pennsylvania's Perelman School of Medicine, told Caijing, this is the global medical community to face a "perfect storm. ".

The reason for this inference, Endy points out, is, in the first place, "We have no prevention strategies other than quarantine, such as vaccines. There is also no means to detect the virus in a timely and early manner, and we do not have all the knowledge needed to know how the virus spreads, including the possibility of asymptomatic transmission; there is no specific treatment for the damage caused by the new coronavirus to the human organ system, which can only be dealt with through supportive treatment by doctors and medical institutions; finally, we still do not have animal models to test how to treat and detect the new coronavirus, and the lack of animal models impedes our ability to move quickly in the areas of immunity, early detection and treatment."

Nancy Messonnier, director of the CDC's National Center for Immunization and respiratory disease, also said at a Feb. 25 media briefing, "The question is not whether the epidemic will spread in the United States, but when it will start and how many people in the country will become seriously ill, " she added, warning that "the disruption to daily life can be severe. "

The Centers for Disease Control and prevention also warned that if the new coronavirus spreads widely in the United States, it could mean large numbers of people requiring medical attention at the same time, this will have an impact on many aspects of society, such as health care, schools, transportation, law enforcement, emergency response, etc. . In addition, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention is working to provide state and local laboratories with a new version of the new coronavirus test kit, some of which were defective.

London Breed, San Francisco's mayor, declared a state of emergency on February 25 amid fears of a new outbreak of pneumonia. While San Francisco has no confirmed cases, Bridger said in a statement, "the global situation is changing rapidly and we need to step up our preparedness. ".

Jeffrey Young, former global head of foreign exchange at Citigroup and co-founder and CEO of Deepmacro, told Caijing that the continued spread of the virus outside China could worsen market sentiment. The CDC's warning is important because if the outbreak leads to tighter travel restrictions, it could have a more serious negative impact on the economy.

Affected by the rapid development of the epidemic, U. S. stocks suffered a series of heavy losses. Dow Jones Industrial Average closed down 879.40, or 3.15 percent, at 27,081.36 after dropping more than 1,000 points on Feb. 24, while the S & P 500 index closed down 97.70, or 3.03 percent, at 3,128.21, down 6.3 percent in two sessions, the Nasdaq ended down 255.70 points, or 2.77 percent, at 8,965.61.

In an effort to calm markets, Kudlow, the White House's chief economic adviser, said on Feb. 25 that the U.S. economy was in good shape and that the administration had contained the COVID-19 outbreak. He urged everyone "not to panic" . "Our economy is in good shape, " he said. "The virus won't last. We've got it under control. I'm not going to say it's watertight, but these measures are very close to watertight. The United States is doing very well. " He added: Although the outbreak is a "human tragedy" , it may not be an "economic tragedy" in his view.

Jeffery young believes the Fed and treasury will have to resort to more "permissive" tools, like a series of measures by the Chinese government against banks, and important normalisation indicators to stabilise the market, the latest data from China's major industrial provinces such as Guangdong and Zhejiang are in good shape. The hope for a sustained upturn is that either the epidemic in China stabilises or the rest of the world moves quickly.
